-- Article 40: Benign Colorectal Diseases
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

EPIDEMIOLOGY: Increases with age - over 50% by age 60. Most common in sigmoid colon in Western populations. Associated with low-fiber diet.

COMPLICATIONS: Diverticulitis (inflammation), abscess formation, perforation, peritonitis, fistula (colovesical most common in males), stricture, hemorrhage (usually painless, from right-sided diverticula).

HINCHEY CLASSIFICATION (Diverticulitis): Stage I - pericolic abscess; Stage II - pelvic abscess; Stage III - purulent peritonitis; Stage IV - fecal peritonitis.

MANAGEMENT: Uncomplicated diverticulitis - antibiotics, clear liquids, bowel rest. Complicated (abscess over 4cm) - CT-guided drainage. Recurrent or complicated - elective sigmoid resection. Emergency - Hartmann procedure (sigmoid resection with end colostomy) or primary anastomosis with or without diverting stoma.'),
('d2000040-0000-0000-0000-000000000040'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Colonic Polyps and Polyposis Syndromes', 'POLYP TYPES: Neoplastic (adenomas - tubular, villous, tubulovillous) and non-neoplastic (hyperplastic, inflammatory, hamartomatous).

ADENOMATOUS POLYPS: Premalignant. Malignancy risk increases with size (over 1cm), villous histology, and high-grade dysplasia. Adenoma-carcinoma sequence is basis for screening colonoscopy.

FAMILIAL ADENOMATOUS POLYPOSIS (FAP): Autosomal dominant, APC gene mutation on chromosome 5. Hundreds to thousands of polyps by teenage years. 100% cancer risk if untreated. Treatment: prophylactic colectomy (total colectomy with ileorectal anastomosis or proctocolectomy with IPAA). Extra-colonic manifestations: desmoid tumors, osteomas, CHRPE (congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium).

HEREDITARY NON-POLYPOSIS COLORECTAL CANCER (HNPCC/Lynch Syndrome): Autosomal dominant, mismatch repair gene mutations (MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2). Right-sided cancers, younger age. Amsterdam criteria for diagnosis. Increased risk of endometrial, ovarian, and other cancers.

PEUTZ-JEGHERS SYNDROME: Hamartomatous polyps plus mucocutaneous pigmentation. Autosomal dominant, STK11 mutation. Increased cancer risk. Polyps may cause intussusception.'),
('d2000040-0000-0000-0000-000000000040'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Inflammatory Bowel Disease', 'ULCERATIVE COLITIS (UC): Mucosal inflammation, continuous from rectum. Bloody diarrhea, urgency, tenesmus. Backwash ileitis may occur. Complications: toxic megacolon, perforation, massive hemorrhage. Cancer risk increases with duration and extent. Extraintestinal: primary sclerosing cholangitis, pyoderma gangrenosum, erythema nodosum, uveitis. Surgery curative: proctocolectomy with IPAA (pouch).

CROHN DISEASE: Transmural inflammation, skip lesions, any part of GI tract (terminal ileum most common). Diarrhea, abdominal pain, weight loss. Complications: strictures, fistulae (enteroenteric, enterocutaneous, perianal), abscess, malabsorption. Cobblestone mucosa, creeping fat. Surgery not curative - resect only for complications. Preserve bowel length.

DISTINGUISHING FEATURES: UC - continuous, rectum always involved, pseudopolyps, crypt abscesses. Crohn - skip lesions, transmural, granulomas, fistulae, terminal ileum.

TOXIC MEGACOLON: Colonic dilation over 6cm with systemic toxicity. Medical emergency. Initial management: IV fluids, steroids, antibiotics, bowel rest, NGT decompression. Surgery if no improvement in 24-72 hours or perforation.'),
('d2000040-0000-0000-0000-000000000040'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'Diverticulitis is left-sided appendicitis. Painless lower GI bleeding suggests right-sided diverticular bleed. Fistula to bladder causes pneumaturia and fecaluria. FAP has 100% cancer risk - prophylactic colectomy needed. Lynch syndrome causes right-sided cancers at younger age. UC is cured by surgery; Crohn is not. Toxic megacolon: over 6cm dilation with toxicity.'),
('d2000040-0000-0000-0000-000000000040'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'Colonic diverticula are false (pulsion) type. Diverticulitis most common in sigmoid. Hinchey classification grades diverticulitis severity. Adenoma-carcinoma sequence underlies colorectal screening. FAP: APC gene, chromosome 5, 100% cancer risk. Lynch syndrome: mismatch repair genes, right-sided cancers. UC: mucosal, continuous; Crohn: transmural, skip lesions. Toxic megacolon is medical emergency requiring close monitoring.');

